CHAPTER 2: OLD FRIENDS
"Ray Carson. Thought you'd be dead by now."
He doesn't look up from his glass. Just raises it slightly in mock salute.
"Working on it."
I sit down two stools away. Light a cigarette. The bartender—skinny kid with neck tattoos and dead eyes—glances over but doesn't say shit. Smart.
Ray finally turns his head. Takes a long look at me. His face is a roadmap of bad decisions—grey stubble, bloodshot eyes, skin that's seen too much sun and not enough sleep. He looks fifty, not forty-two.
"Cole fucking Brennan."
"Ray fucking Carson."
"I heard you were dead."
"I heard YOU were dead."
"Yeah, well." He pours another drink, hand shaking just slightly. "Still working on it."
I take a drag. Exhale. The smoke hangs between us like a ghost.
"You look like shit, Ray."
"And you look like a banker who fucks his secretary." He finally cracks something that might be a smile. "Oh wait, you don't have a secretary."
"Explains the suit."
"Explains why you're here at two in the morning looking like someone's chasing you."
He's not wrong. I can feel it—that itch between my shoulder blades. The sense that Vincent's people are always watching. Always waiting.
"What do you want, Cole?"
"Can't I just—"
"No." He cuts me off. "You can't 'just.' Friends check in. Friends don't disappear for four fucking years and show up in a dive bar at midnight looking like they just walked out of a funeral."
"Three and a half years."
"Fuck you."
"See? That's the Ray I remember."
He pours another drink. The bottle's already half empty. I wonder if that's from tonight or if he just never bothers to finish one before starting the next.
"Get to the point or get the fuck out."
I tap ash into the tray between us. Consider how to say this. There's no good way.
"I need your help."
Ray laughs. It's sharp and bitter and hollow—the sound of something breaking.
"My help. Yeah. Sure. Let me just—" He mimes looking around the bar. "—grab my cape and my badge and my give-a-shit. Oh wait, I don't have any of those anymore."
"You still got your brain."
"My brain's pickled."
"Not THAT pickled. You remember Vincent Harlan?"
The glass stops halfway to his mouth. Everything about him goes still—prey animal sensing a predator.
"...What did you just say?"
"Vincent Harlan. The Broker. You remember him, right? Or did the whiskey take that too?"
"Don't—" His voice drops to something dangerous. "Don't say that name. Not here. Not anywhere."
"Why? He own this place too?"
"He owns everything. Which is why whatever you're planning is fucking suicide."
I lean closer. Lower my voice.
"I'm not planning suicide, Ray. I'm planning war."
"What the fuck does that mean?"
"It means I'm hitting him. Not directly—I'm not that stupid. But his network. His people. The cops on his payroll, the properties he uses, the accounts he hides behind. I'm going to take it apart piece by piece until there's nothing left."
Ray stares at me. Then starts laughing again—but this time it's worse. Manic. The laugh of someone who's seen the punchline and knows it ends in blood.
"Oh my God. OH MY GOD. You've completely lost your fucking mind."
"Probably."
"You can't touch Harlan. People—SMART people, CONNECTED people—have tried. You know what happened to them?"
"They're dead."
"They're GONE. As in, no bodies, no evidence, no nothing. Poof. Like they never existed." He downs his drink. "And you think you can—what? Just waltz in and dismantle him?"
"I think I can learn how he operates. Map his network. Find the weak points. And yes—dismantle him."
"With what army?"
"With you."
"Me." He gestures at himself—the stained jacket, the shaking hands, the empty bottles. "Look at me, Cole. I'm not an army. I'm barely a person."
"You went undercover in his operations. You saw the whole thing from the inside. You know which cops are dirty, which routes they use, how the money flows. That's all in your head."
"I know jack shit. I've been drunk for three years. My memory's—"
"Bullshit." I cut him off. "You remember everything. That's your problem. You can't forget, so you drink to try."
His jaw clenches. I've hit something.
"Fuck you."
"Ricardo Navarro. Marcus Webb. The Downtown Strangler case. The Riverside laundering ring. The—"
"STOP."
"See? You remember."
"I said STOP."
The bar goes quiet. Even the jukebox seems to lower its volume. The bartender looks over, nervous.
Ray's breathing hard. Staring at his glass like it holds answers.
"What happened?" I ask quietly. "After you came back. You just... disappeared."
"I didn't disappear." His voice is raw now. No more sarcasm. Just pain. "I got burned. Department threw me out like garbage. My partner—my BEST FRIEND—testified against me in the internal investigation. Said I'd gone native, couldn't be trusted. My wife left. Took everything. My mom—" He stops. Swallows hard. "My mom doesn't even recognize me anymore. Dementia. I go visit her and she thinks I'm the fucking doctor."
"Jesus, Ray."
"Yeah. Jesus. So yeah, Cole, I disappeared. Because there was nothing left to fucking FIND."
I let the silence sit for a moment. Then:
"There's this."
"This? WHAT IS THIS? Some half-baked revenge fantasy?"
"It's a chance to burn down the system that destroyed you."
"By destroying myself faster? Great plan."
"You're already dying here." I gesture at the bottles, the bar, the whole sad picture. "At least die doing something that matters."
Before he can answer, a voice cuts through the bar.
"The fuck you two fags whispering about over there?"
We both turn. There's a guy three stools down—mid-forties, beer gut, stained Dodgers jersey. Drunk. The aggressive kind. He's staring at us with that look drunk assholes get when they decide they need to prove something.
Ray doesn't even look up. Just says flatly:
"Your mother's OnlyFans. Disappointing content."
I almost laugh.
The drunk's face goes red. "The FUCK did you say?"
"He said your mother's a whore," I add helpfully. "Which, given your face, checks out. Genetics don't lie."
The guy stands up, swaying. Tries to look tough. Probably works on other drunks.
"You wanna fucking GO?"
Ray moves faster than I've seen him move in years.
One second he's sitting there with his drink. The next his hand shoots out, grabs the back of the drunk's head, and SLAMS it down onto the bar.
The crack echoes. Blood spatters. The drunk's nose is definitely broken.
Ray holds him there, face pressed against the wood, blood pooling around his cheek.
"You know what I hate?" Ray's voice is conversational. Almost friendly. "Loud people. Can't stand them. All that noise, all that mouth, and nothing useful coming out." He presses down harder. The drunk whimpers. "See, I used to put people in rooms and ask them questions. And sometimes they'd be loud. Like you. And I'd have to teach them about volume control."
"Ray." I don't move. Just smoke my cigarette. "We talked about this."
"Right. Right." He lets go suddenly. Steps back. "My bad. Indoor voice."
The drunk stumbles backward, hands over his face, blood streaming between his fingers. He makes a sound—half sob, half moan—and stumbles toward the bathroom.
Ray sits back down. Picks up his drink like nothing happened.
"Where were we?"
The bartender appears, face pale. "You need to leave. Now."
I pull out my wallet. Count out five hundred-dollar bills. Drop them on the bar.
"That cover his medical bills? And your silence?"
The bartender stares at the money. It's probably more than he makes in a week. Maybe two.
"...Yeah. We're good."
"Thought so."
He grabs the cash and disappears. Fast.
I look at Ray. "Feel better?"
"Little bit." He flexes his hand. Knuckles already starting to bruise. "Fucker called us fags."
"We were whispering."
"Still rude."
I can't help it. I laugh. Actually laugh. First time in weeks.
"There he is," Ray says, studying me. "The Cole I remember. Thought Vincent killed that guy."
"He did. I'm just the ghost wearing his clothes."
"Ghosts can't smoke."
"Then call me a zombie."
"Zombies don't plan heists."
"Then I don't know what the fuck I am anymore."
Ray pours another drink. Stares at it. Doesn't drink yet.
"What happened to you, Cole? Really. Why now?"
I take a long drag. Might as well tell him.
"Vincent wanted me to do a job. Launder twenty million for a cartel operation. Fentanyl deal. Would've killed hundreds. Maybe thousands. I said no."
"First time?"
"First time in six years."
"And he didn't take it well."
"He threatened my family. Sarah. Emma. Ryan. Direct threats. Not subtle. So Sarah packed up the kids and left. Told me not to come back until I could promise they'd be safe. Really safe. Forever."
Ray's quiet for a moment.
"Where are they?"
"I don't know. She won't tell me. Probably smart."
"Fuck."
"Yeah."
"And you think hitting Vincent's network is gonna bring them back?"
"No." I crush out my cigarette. "I think it's the only way to make sure Vincent can't find them. If I can take apart his organization, expose his connections, burn it all down—maybe they can come home. Maybe Emma can go to college without looking over her shoulder. Maybe Ryan can grow up believing his dad was something other than a coward."
Ray stares into his glass.
"How many people you got for this suicide mission?"
"You'd be number two."
He laughs again. That broken sound. "Two. TWO PEOPLE. Against Vincent Harlan's entire empire. His cops, his lawyers, his politicians, his fucking ARMY."
"One job," I say. "That's all I'm asking. You and me. We hit one of his people. Someone low-level. Learn what we can. See if it works. If it doesn't—if I'm full of shit and we're gonna die—you can go back to drowning here."
"And if it does work?"
"Then we figure out the next step."
"This is insane."
"I know."
"We're gonna die."
"Probably."
"I haven't done anything like this since—" He stops. Something dark crosses his face. "Since before everything went to shit."
"So what do you say?"
Long silence. The jukebox plays something sad and country. A couple in the corner argues in whispers. The bartender stays in the back.
Ray picks up his glass. Holds it. Studies the amber liquid like it's a crystal ball.
Then he sets it down. Doesn't drink.
"When?"
Relief hits me like a punch. "Tomorrow night. I'll text you where."
"I'm gonna regret this."
"Oh, absolutely."
"I'm serious. This is the stupidest thing I've ever done. And I once went undercover with the Armenian mob for six months."
"How'd that go?"
"Got stabbed twice and developed a drinking problem." He almost smiles. "So, you know. Great track record."
"Third time's the charm."
"Fuck you, Cole."
"Fuck you too, Ray."
I stand. Drop some more cash on the bar—enough to cover both our tabs and then some.
"Don't die tonight."
"No promises."
"I'm serious. You die before tomorrow, I'm gonna be pissed."
"Why? You need me that bad?"
"Yeah. I do."
He looks up at me. Something shifts in his eyes. The first hint of something other than resignation.
"You really think we can hurt him?"
"I think we can try. And trying is better than dying slowly in this shithole."
"Motivational."
"I'm not a motivational speaker. I'm a money launderer planning to rob the guy who owns me." I head for the door. "See you tomorrow, Ray."
"Cole."
I stop. Turn back.
"Thanks."
"For what?"
"For still being an asshole. Makes me feel less alone."
I flip him off. He returns it.
I walk out into the cold LA night. Get in my car. Light another cigarette.
My phone buzzes. Text from an unknown number: Still watching. Don't do anything stupid. -V
Vincent. Always watching.
I delete it. Start the car.
Tomorrow, Ray and I go to work.

Inside the bar, Ray sits alone. The drunk guy staggers out of the bathroom, takes one look at Ray, and leaves through the back door.
The bartender keeps his distance.
Ray stares at his full glass. Then at the bottle. Then at his hands—still shaking, but not as bad.
He reaches into his jacket. Pulls out an old notebook. Leather cover worn to shit, pages yellowed and bent. He hasn't opened it in three years. Didn't think he ever would again.
He opens it.
Page after page of notes. Names. Addresses. Dates. Everything he learned going undercover in Vincent Harlan's world. Everything he tried to give the department before they burned him.
He pulls out a pen. Starts writing. Adding. Remembering.
All the things he wished he could forget.
All the things Cole is going to need.
He writes for an hour. Then two. The bottle sits untouched.
Finally, he closes the notebook. Looks at the glass one more time.
Pushes it away.
"Fuck it," he says to no one. "If I'm gonna die, might as well take some bastards with me."
He leaves the money on the bar. Walks out into the same cold night.
For the first time in three years, Ray Carson has somewhere to be tomorrow.
